stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: Analysis of Zeus Malware Artifact
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
On 01 April 2013, a file was submitted for analysis. The file was a Zeus trojan that after being executed on a victim's machine, steals user data and communicates with twenty (20) hard-coded IP addresses.
This document incorporates data originally released as US-CERT MAR-272580.

stix:Indicator.indicator:Description:
Stage 1. The malware allocates space on the heap, copies the malicious code there and jumps to that code.
Stage 2. The malware modifies itself by overwriting ".text" section, and performs injections into the multiple processes including "explorer.exe" process.
The malware resolves addresses of the following APIs: GetProcAddress LoadLibraryExA LoadLibraryExW GetModuleHandleA CreateFileA lstrcatA GetWindowsDirectoryA GetModuleHandleW memcpy memset VirtualAlloc UnmapViewOfFile VirtualProtect HeapAlloc GetProcessHeap
Next, the malware allocates space on the heap, copies data there and decodes it by xor'ing it with 0x3E9. After that, the malware resolves addresses of many APIs from the following libraries: ntdll.dll kernel32.dll user32.dll advapi32.dll shlwapi.dll shell32.dll secure32.dll ole32.dll gdi32.dll ws2_32.dll crypt32.dll wininet.dll oleauth32.dll netapi32.dll iphlpapi.dll version.dll msvcrt.dll
The malware has capability to encrypt/decrypt data by using RC4 algorithm. Additionally, the malware uses CRC32, SHA1, and MD5 algorithms. To calculate the SHA1 and MD5 the malware uses "advapi32" APIs: "CryptAcquireContext", "CryptCreateHash", "CryptHashData", "CryptDestroyHash", and "CryptReleaseContext".
The malware allocates more space on the heap, copies, and decodes data there. Within this data the malware searches for string "DAVE" comparing four (4) bytes of the data to "DAVE" at the time.
The malware creates named Mutex object (this is non‐persistent name, based on the unique system's volume GUID): 0012EF14 18 40 00 00 4C 00 6F 00 63 00 61 00 6C 00 5C 00 L.o.c.a.l.\. 0012EF24 7B 00 31 00 36 00 45 00 41 00 37 00 42 00 30 00 {.1.6.E.A.7.B.0. 0012EF34 30 00 2D 00 41 00 45 00 44 00 42 00 2D 00 36 00 0.‐.A.E.D.B.‐.6. 0012EF44 41 00 46 00 32 00 2D 00 34 00 46 00 37 00 38 00 A.F.2.‐.4.F.7.8. 0012EF54 2D 00 37 00 32 00 39 00 33 00 35 00 46 00 30 00 ‐.7.2.9.3.5.F.0. 0012EF64 42 00 35 00 31 00 38 00 31 00 7D 00 00 00 12 00 B.5.1.8.1.}
Next, the malware opens or creates (if it does not exist) "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Xelar" registry key, and adds the following sub key: [HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Xelar] "1924dgh5"="8uDKhJGD9QTldEGRSxk=" After that the malware performs code injection into the "explorer.exe" process.
Interesting strings from the Stage 2: "1cj2hbd3" "1924dgh5" "CHSI‐R96NBNT_704B724673CB7785536289B4571E660F" "gnomm25" "Software\Microsoft" "Xelar" "h51924dgh5" "8uDKhJGD9QTldEGRSxk=" "Global\{D5042C0E‐F9D5‐A91C‐2065‐B06D3016937F}"
Stage 3 The malware runs multi‐threaded in this stage. The main thread in the victim's process. The malware installs user‐land hooks for the following APIs: closesocket send WSASend recv WSARecv WSAGetOverlappedResult DeleteSecurityContext EncryptMessage DecryptMessage TranslateMessage GetClipboardData PFXImportCertStore GetAddrInfoW getaddrinfo FreeAddrInfoW ‐ this function is actually hooked twice. gethostbyname NtCreateThread LdrLoadDll
Additionally, the malware has capability to hook the following APIs from "nspr4.dll" (associated with Mozilla Firefox): PR_OpenTCPSocket PR_Close PR_Poll PR_Read PR_Write PR_GetNameForIdentity PR_SetError PR_GetError PR_GetSocketOption The malware also has capability to hook up APIs from "chrome.dll".
Thread 1 in the victim's process. Creates named Mutex object "Global\{3C924B09‐9ED2‐408A‐4F78‐72935F0B5181}". The malware opens "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Xelar" registry key, and tries to enumerate data in the "1cj2hbd3" sub key if it exists. If it does not exist the malware adds new sub key: [HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Xelar] "1cj2hbd3"=dword:84a4e085
Decodes/decrypts/calculates following interesting strings in the Thread 1: "Global\" "Software\Microsoft" "Xelar" "1cj2hbd3"
Thread 2 in the victim's process. In this Thread the malware creates firewall exception for itself and opens up one TCP and one UDP ports for the incoming and outgoing connections. The malware also makes multiple C2 callbacks. The malware creates named Mutex object "Global\{8C404922‐9CF9‐F058‐4F78‐72935F0B5181}". The malware opens "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Xelar" registry key, and tries to enumerate following sub keys: "2hi8hegg", "2e175j8e", "17f8dbg", and "2cijh32b".
Then the malware notifies OS that it is interested in receiving notifications about the FD_READ and FD_WRITE events. The malware checks to see if the firewall allows exceptions and changes local policy to create an exception for itself.
Payload creation. Following data is hashed (SHA1) in 3 (three) chunks: The first chunk (size 0x14), is the same for all the callbacks: 003A1CB8 33 4A 10 41 40 44 12 BE 7D 41 55 5C 26 8C 1B 19 3J.A@D.+}AU\&î.. 003A1CC8 EA 9A FD 5E 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 96 30 07 77 OÜ²^
The second chunk (size 0x8), is different from callback to callback: For example: 0117F748 FE C2 42 33 2F BA 06 00 The third chunk (size 0x4), is different from callback to callback:
For example: 0117F754 6E 7B 34 06
The resulting SHA1 is: 4F DA EE A5 7E 1E BB 11 E1 1E 2D 9C 15 16 A3 BC 6A DA F9 1B
The malware has several hard coded IP addresses and port numbers which it calls out to with a specially crafted payload.
